    "last_activity_date" : 1376264179,
    "creation_date" : 1376264179,
    "answer_id" : 18177784,
    "question_id" : 2444359,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Along with sorted key store one another difference is with TreeMap, developer can give (String.CASE_INSENSITIVE_ORDER) with String keys, so then the comparator ignores case of key while performing comparison of keys on map access. This is not possible to give such option with HashMap - it is always case sensitive comparisons in HashMap.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2351754,
      "reputation" : 355,
      "user_id" : 2060386,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 43,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/700be9fa778452227f9cbe62f25a2a1e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "user2060386",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2060386/user2060386"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1395698202,
    "creation_date" : 1395698202,
    "answer_id" : 22621445,
    "question_id" : 2444359,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I'll talk about the <strong>HashMap</strong> and <strong>TreeMap</strong> implementation in Java:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>HashMap -- implement basic map interface</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>implemented by an array of buckets, each bucket is a LinkedList of entries </li>\n<li>running time of basic operations: put(), average O(1), worst case O(n), happens when the table is resized; get(), remove(), average O(1) </li>\n<li>not synchronized, to synchronize it: <code>Map m = Collections.synchronizedMap(new HashMap(...));</code></li>\n<li>Iteration order of the map is unpredictable.  </li>\n</ol></li>\n<li><p>TreeMap -- implement navigable map interface</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>implemented by a red-black tree</li>\n<li>running time of basic operations: put(), get(), remove(), worst case O(lgn)</li>\n<li>not synchronized, to synchronize it: <code>SortedMap m = Collections.synchronizedSortedMap(new TreeMap(...));</code></li>\n<li>provide ordered iteration. higherKey(), lowerKey() can be used to get the successor and predecessor of a given key.</li>\n</ol></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>To sum, the biggest difference between HashMap and TreeMap is that TreeMap implements <code>NavigableMap&lt;K,V&gt;</code>, which provide the feature of ordered iteration. Besides, both HashMap and TreeMap are members of Java Collection framework. You can investigate the <a href=\"http://grepcode.com/file/repository.grepcode.com/java/root/jdk/openjdk/6-b14/java/util/HashMap.java#HashMap.KeyIterator.next%28%29\">source code of Java</a> to know more about their implementations. </p>\n"
  }, {
